                <head>142. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On February 27, at the 356th meeting of the National Security Council, with the
                    President presiding, <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName>, in his
                    review of significant world developments affecting U.S. security, raised the
                    question of the recent elections in Argentina. The memorandum of discussion
                    reads as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Turning to the recent Argentine election, Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> stated that <persName
                                corresp="#p_FA1">Frondizi</persName> had actually won more
                            decisively than had been contemplated prior to the returns. He had very
                            nearly secured a clear majority <pb facs="0508" n="468" xml:id="pg_468"
                            /> of the votes. He got the Peronista vote and most of the Communist
                            vote. <persName corresp="#p_FA1">Frondizi</persName> made a deal with
                            Peron during the campaign—allegedly in writing. In general he had
                            promised that the Peronista Party would be legal, and that he would
                            grant a general amnesty to Peronistas. Of course, we do not know whether
                            he will keep his word, but unless the United States is able to exert
                            some real influence on <persName corresp="#p_FA1">Frondizi</persName>,
                            he is likely to take Argentina along a neutralist path. Of course, it
                            was possible that he may change views when he assumes the
                            responsibilities of his office.” (Memorandum of discussion at the 356th
                            meeting of the National Security Council, February 28; Eisenhower
                            Library, Whitman File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
